explanation: opendir — needed to know its failure semantics (whether it can return NULL or have other control-flow side effects) so the if (dp == NULL) branch is meaningful for reachability. DIR — the return type of opendir; its definition may affect assumptions about opendir semantics or macros that wrap it. OS_object_token_t — the token type is dereferenced (*token); its definition determines whether that dereference is well-formed or may be a no-op/macro that changes control flow. OS_impl_dir_internal_record_t — the structure type for impl; needed to confirm the existence and type of the dp field and whether writing impl->dp is reachable/valid. OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET — macro/function used to obtain impl; its expansion could contain control-flow (returns, longjmp, assertions) or side effects that make subsequent statements unreachable, so its definition is required. OS_impl_dir_table — the table argument passed to OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; its definition may affect the macro expansion and whether the call can short-circuit control flow. OS_ERROR — the value returned on dp == NULL; required to ensure the return is a normal return and not a macro that alters control flow. OS_SUCCESS — the final return value; needed to ensure the final return is reachable and not replaced by a macro with side effects. OS_ObjectIndexFromToken — present in the static call graph (likely used inside OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET); its implementation may include control-flow constructs (errors/returns) that affect reachability of code after the table-get call.
